00:10:34.040 --> 00:10:36.070
I may need you to run out
and take care of this.

00:10:36.070 --> 00:10:38.300
But I'm going to try
and keep it here.

00:10:38.300 --> 00:10:40.440
So we'll keep an eye on that.

00:10:40.440 --> 00:10:43.550
whisky, I mentioned, produced
through the fermentation of

00:10:43.550 --> 00:10:46.180
barley, primarily.

00:10:46.180 --> 00:10:47.050
Barley.

00:10:47.050 --> 00:10:51.340
I used honey because honey
has a nice sugar content.

00:10:51.340 --> 00:10:53.850
Barley, not so much.

00:10:53.850 --> 00:10:55.360
Not a lot of sugar in barley.

00:10:55.360 --> 00:10:56.800
So we'll talk about
that in a minute.

00:10:56.800 --> 00:10:59.200
I want you to keep that
in mind, where is

00:10:59.200 --> 00:11:02.020
the sugar in barley?

00:11:02.020 --> 00:11:03.280
But that's later.

00:11:03.280 --> 00:11:05.360
So steps to making whisky.

00:11:05.360 --> 00:11:06.880
First thing you need
to do is take that

00:11:06.880 --> 00:11:08.440
barley and mash it up.

00:11:08.440 --> 00:11:09.700
You need to break the husks.

00:11:09.700 --> 00:11:12.620
You need to get to the middle
of the barley where all the

00:11:12.620 --> 00:11:13.650
good stuff is.

00:11:13.650 --> 00:11:17.250
That's called mashing
or washing.

00:11:17.250 --> 00:11:20.060
And that produces a liquid
called wort.

00:11:20.060 --> 00:11:23.300
It's spelled "wort," but it's
actually pronounced "wert."

00:11:23.300 --> 00:11:26.350
And that is a small mash tun.

00:11:26.350 --> 00:11:28.670
This is a large mash tun.

00:11:28.670 --> 00:11:31.560
This is the Glenfiddich
Distillery in Scotland.

00:11:31.560 --> 00:11:33.430
I was just there a
few weeks ago.

00:11:33.430 --> 00:11:34.570
These are enormous.

00:11:34.570 --> 00:11:35.820
You can see the scale.

00:11:38.340 --> 00:11:43.510
Once you have that wort, you
then pitch the yeast just like

00:11:43.510 --> 00:11:44.090
I did here.

00:11:44.090 --> 00:11:47.020
And you can see that yeast
cap is growing.

00:11:47.020 --> 00:11:48.930
And it begins to ferment.

00:11:48.930 --> 00:11:50.970
It's usually done in
an open container

00:11:50.970 --> 00:11:53.020
just like that glass.

00:11:53.020 --> 00:12:00.160
This cap of CO2 essentially
forms a cover on top of the

00:12:00.160 --> 00:12:02.440
wort so nothing else
can get in there.

00:12:02.440 --> 00:12:07.170
Once this fermentation starts,
this is as good as sealed.

00:12:07.170 --> 00:12:10.180
So even though this is called
open fermentation because it

00:12:10.180 --> 00:12:14.710
is an open vessel, it's actually
a closed system.

00:12:14.710 --> 00:12:17.350
This is a layer of CO2 that
keeps anything else from

00:12:17.350 --> 00:12:18.990
getting in there.

00:12:18.990 --> 00:12:21.860
So open fermentation is
still used today.

00:12:21.860 --> 00:12:24.630
This is actually the Maker's
Mark distillery, I believe, is

00:12:24.630 --> 00:12:25.880
where I took that picture.

00:12:28.170 --> 00:12:31.110
So I mentioned how
fermentation--

00:12:31.110 --> 00:12:33.360
fermentation produces beer.

00:12:33.360 --> 00:12:35.920
Fermentation produces wine.

00:12:35.920 --> 00:12:38.060
Fermentation produces cider.

00:12:38.060 --> 00:12:40.730
And fermentation
produces mead.

00:12:40.730 --> 00:12:43.920
Those are our four basic
fermented beverages.

00:12:43.920 --> 00:12:46.140
Beer is from barley.

00:12:46.140 --> 00:12:48.136
Cider is from what?

00:12:48.136 --> 00:12:48.540
AUDIENCE: Fruits.

00:12:48.540 --> 00:12:49.440
ANTHONY CAPORALE: Fruits.

00:12:49.440 --> 00:12:49.920
Good.

00:12:49.920 --> 00:12:52.820
Pomaceous fruits, usually
apples, pears.

00:12:52.820 --> 00:12:54.650
Wine, we all know
from grapes--

00:12:54.650 --> 00:12:57.380
berries, actually, but
mostly grapes.

00:12:57.380 --> 00:12:58.380
And mead.

00:12:58.380 --> 00:12:59.220
I mentioned mead.

00:12:59.220 --> 00:13:01.340
What is mead produced from?

00:13:01.340 --> 00:13:02.220
Honey.

00:13:02.220 --> 00:13:04.530
That's what I'm making
right here.

00:13:04.530 --> 00:13:05.310
This is mead.

00:13:05.310 --> 00:13:07.810
We think mead is probably
the oldest of all

00:13:07.810 --> 00:13:09.180
the fermented beverages.

00:13:09.180 --> 00:13:12.170
But the thing about fermented
beverages, folks, is because

00:13:12.170 --> 00:13:17.900
alcohol is toxic, they stop
at a certain ABV.

00:13:17.900 --> 00:13:20.200
The yeast goes dormant
or dies.

00:13:20.200 --> 00:13:25.160
So you've never have wine at
higher than about 18% alcohol.

00:13:25.160 --> 00:13:28.910
Beer, in America, 5%
or 6% alcohol.

00:13:28.910 --> 00:13:31.040
If you want to go higher than
that, if you want to get to

00:13:31.040 --> 00:13:35.650
that 40% alcohol or even higher,
you have to physically

00:13:35.650 --> 00:13:37.580
pull the alcohol out.

00:13:37.580 --> 00:13:39.740
You have to separate
the alcohol from

00:13:39.740 --> 00:13:40.830
the rest of the liquid.

00:13:40.830 --> 00:13:44.490
And you do that through a
process called distillation.

00:13:44.490 --> 00:13:48.900
And that's really the core
of the spirits industry.

00:13:48.900 --> 00:13:52.730
Distillation separates liquids
based on a difference in

00:13:52.730 --> 00:13:53.840
boiling point.

00:13:53.840 --> 00:13:56.760
So we know water, for example,
boils at about 212 degrees

00:13:56.760 --> 00:13:57.790
Fahrenheit.

00:13:57.790 --> 00:14:01.350
Turns out that ethyl alcohol
boils at 173.

00:14:01.350 --> 00:14:06.790
So if I heat a mixture of ethyl
alcohol and water--

00:14:06.790 --> 00:14:12.420
if I heat this mixture to about
175, the ethyl alcohol

00:14:12.420 --> 00:14:15.130
will turn into a gas.

00:14:15.130 --> 00:14:16.130
It will boil.

00:14:16.130 --> 00:14:19.520
The water will remain liquid.

00:14:19.520 --> 00:14:29.230
If I then capture that gas,
that ethyl alcohol gas, in

00:14:29.230 --> 00:14:36.120
something like this and then
cool it back down below 173,

00:14:36.120 --> 00:14:39.260
I've now separated the
ethyl alcohol out.

00:14:39.260 --> 00:14:43.355
And I left back in the
pot just the water.

00:14:43.355 --> 00:14:43.630
OK?

00:14:43.630 --> 00:14:45.580
And that is distillation.

00:14:45.580 --> 00:14:52.360
So I'm actually running here a
distillation demonstration.

00:14:52.360 --> 00:14:57.130
In this pot, I have beer,
plain old beer.

00:14:57.130 --> 00:15:02.050
It's exactly what this will
be in about two days.

00:15:02.050 --> 00:15:02.360
OK?

00:15:02.360 --> 00:15:06.020
So I'm doing the entire process
in front of you.

00:15:06.020 --> 00:15:07.860
I now heat this up.

00:15:07.860 --> 00:15:10.582
This is going to heat
to about 180.

00:15:10.582 --> 00:15:14.040
The ethyl alcohol will turn into
a gas captured down here.

00:15:14.040 --> 00:15:16.750
This is ice that will
cool it back down.

00:15:16.750 --> 00:15:19.580
And dripping out of here in
just a few minutes will be

00:15:19.580 --> 00:15:21.150
pure ethyl alcohol.

00:15:21.150 --> 00:15:22.570
And I'm going to prove
that it's pure

00:15:22.570 --> 00:15:23.940
ethyl alcohol to you.

00:15:23.940 --> 00:15:25.020
How do you think I'm
going to do that?

00:15:25.020 --> 00:15:26.400
AUDIENCE: Set it on fire.

00:15:26.400 --> 00:15:28.040
ANTHONY CAPORALE: Same way
the tax collectors did.

00:15:28.040 --> 00:15:28.970
Exactly right.

00:15:28.970 --> 00:15:30.330
So somebody keep
an eye on that.

00:15:30.330 --> 00:15:31.610
Can you see that from
where you are?

00:15:31.610 --> 00:15:33.570
You let me know if that
starts dripping.

00:15:33.570 --> 00:15:34.660
OK, great.

00:15:34.660 --> 00:15:38.110
So that is distillation.

00:15:38.110 --> 00:15:41.650
So, these so far are all the
basic steps to making whisky.

00:15:41.650 --> 00:15:43.870
I have cereal grains.

00:15:43.870 --> 00:15:47.800
I mash them, mix them up with
water, and break them down.

00:15:47.800 --> 00:15:50.970
I ferment them, and then
I distill them.

00:15:50.970 --> 00:15:53.840
Unfortunately, all I have at
that point is moonshine.

00:15:53.840 --> 00:15:58.510
I have just a clear distillate
that's very harsh and very

00:15:58.510 --> 00:15:59.700
difficult to drink.

00:15:59.700 --> 00:16:02.490
In order to turn it into
whisky, I need

00:16:02.490 --> 00:16:04.570
to age it in wood.

00:16:04.570 --> 00:16:06.150
And that's where the
magic happens.

00:16:06.150 --> 00:16:09.410
This is basically a diagram of a
laboratory version of what I

00:16:09.410 --> 00:16:11.900
have going on right there.

00:16:11.900 --> 00:16:13.680
This is my favorite still in the
whole world because I'm a

00:16:13.680 --> 00:16:14.900
huge "MASH" fan.

00:16:14.900 --> 00:16:17.510
And it shows you how simple
this technology is, folks.

00:16:17.510 --> 00:16:19.470
This is actually based on
a true story. "MASH" was

00:16:19.470 --> 00:16:21.010
actually based on
true stories.

00:16:21.010 --> 00:16:23.770
This was actually a war
zone in a tent, right?

00:16:23.770 --> 00:16:27.600
And they were actually making
distillations in a

00:16:27.600 --> 00:16:29.150
war zone in a tent.

00:16:29.150 --> 00:16:30.580
This is the Glenfiddich
Distillery

00:16:30.580 --> 00:16:32.310
in Speyside, Scotland.

00:16:32.310 --> 00:16:35.920
These pot stills are exactly
the same as those, except

00:16:35.920 --> 00:16:37.170
they're giant.

00:16:39.440 --> 00:16:41.180
The second type of distillation
I'm going to

00:16:41.180 --> 00:16:45.220
mention very, very briefly
is column distillation.

00:16:45.220 --> 00:16:48.680
This is called a pot
still, a pot still.

00:16:48.680 --> 00:16:50.610
It's also called
a batch still.

00:16:50.610 --> 00:16:52.580
And that's because you
do it in batches.

00:16:52.580 --> 00:16:54.250
You put some beer in here.

00:16:54.250 --> 00:16:55.300
You distill it.

00:16:55.300 --> 00:16:58.160
You empty this out, and
then you do it again.

00:16:58.160 --> 00:17:00.900
Really, really great, but it
doesn't work so well for

00:17:00.900 --> 00:17:02.590
industrial settings.

00:17:02.590 --> 00:17:04.930
Because you have to keep
starting it and stopping it.

00:17:04.930 --> 00:17:06.640
We're doing pretty good
on this, yeah?

00:17:06.640 --> 00:17:08.569
Happens pretty quickly.

00:17:08.569 --> 00:17:11.770
You have to keep starting
it and stopping it.

00:17:11.770 --> 00:17:15.780
They came up with another way to
distill beverages based on

00:17:15.780 --> 00:17:19.060
heat exchange that allows you to
consistently pump the beer

00:17:19.060 --> 00:17:23.290
in and pull the alcohol out
because they have steam coming

00:17:23.290 --> 00:17:25.670
in from the top, distillate
coming in from the bottom.

00:17:25.670 --> 00:17:27.619
And you can just keep the
whole process going.

00:17:27.619 --> 00:17:31.230
This is called a column
or continuous still.

00:17:31.230 --> 00:17:35.230
We use this for grain
whiskies, generally.

00:17:35.230 --> 00:17:37.930
So for those of you who are
really, really into scotches,

00:17:37.930 --> 00:17:41.440
we have malt scotches and
we have grain scotches.

00:17:41.440 --> 00:17:43.900
Malt scotches are generally
made from barley.

00:17:43.900 --> 00:17:46.140
Grain scotches are generally
made from wheat.

00:17:46.140 --> 00:17:48.330
They're lighter, and they're
a little cleaner.

00:17:48.330 --> 00:17:51.080
If you're going for a lighter,
cleaner style of spirit,

00:17:51.080 --> 00:17:53.390
you're going to use
a column still.

00:17:53.390 --> 00:17:56.690
If you're going for a more
character-based style of

00:17:56.690 --> 00:18:00.680
spirit, you're going to use a
pot still or a batch still.

00:18:00.680 --> 00:18:04.110
So I just mention that so you
guys can be familiar with what

00:18:04.110 --> 00:18:05.780
the two types of distillation
are.

00:18:05.780 --> 00:18:09.370
This is what one actually
looks like in the field.

00:18:09.370 --> 00:18:12.990
And now we have our distillate
that actually comes out as

00:18:12.990 --> 00:18:15.690
what we call new whisky
or green whisky.

00:18:15.690 --> 00:18:20.360
This then gets put
in a barrel.

00:18:20.360 --> 00:18:23.860
Barrels were generally
used for wine, right?

00:18:23.860 --> 00:18:26.260
Barrels were used to age wine.

00:18:26.260 --> 00:18:29.990
I want you to remember
that wine was only

00:18:29.990 --> 00:18:31.960
reserved for the rich.

00:18:31.960 --> 00:18:34.400
In general, rich people
drank wine.

00:18:34.400 --> 00:18:36.250
Wine's very expensive to make.

00:18:36.250 --> 00:18:39.420
Grapes are very temperamental,
and it's a very

00:18:39.420 --> 00:18:42.250
labor-intensive process
to make wine.

00:18:42.250 --> 00:18:43.900
So the rich people drank wine.

00:18:43.900 --> 00:18:48.780
Spirits, up until very recently,
were generally

00:18:48.780 --> 00:18:51.130
consumed by the poor, by
the lower classes,

00:18:51.130 --> 00:18:52.870
by the working classes.

00:18:52.870 --> 00:18:56.380
Because all they wanted
was that alcohol kick.

00:18:56.380 --> 00:19:00.430
So what they would do is take
whatever the byproducts that

00:19:00.430 --> 00:19:02.610
happened to be in
the area, they

00:19:02.610 --> 00:19:04.820
would ferment and distill.

00:19:04.820 --> 00:19:06.870
And then they would age them,
and they would end up with

00:19:06.870 --> 00:19:09.320
spirits that were very unique
to whatever regions you

00:19:09.320 --> 00:19:10.300
happened to be in.

00:19:10.300 --> 00:19:14.960
So, for example, in Italy, you
make a ton of wine in Italy.

00:19:14.960 --> 00:19:18.260
The peasants would take
all the byproducts

00:19:18.260 --> 00:19:19.550
of making that wine.

00:19:19.550 --> 00:19:20.840
They would take the seeds.

00:19:20.840 --> 00:19:21.950
They would take the stems.

00:19:21.950 --> 00:19:23.360
They would take the leaves.

00:19:23.360 --> 00:19:25.290
They would take everything that
wasn't actually used in

00:19:25.290 --> 00:19:26.150
making wine.

00:19:26.150 --> 00:19:27.000
They would take that home.

00:19:27.000 --> 00:19:29.250
They would press all
that stuff again.

00:19:29.250 --> 00:19:32.800
And believe it or not, there's
enough residual sugar left in

00:19:32.800 --> 00:19:35.030
those wine byproducts
that they could

00:19:35.030 --> 00:19:37.070
ferment that liquid.

00:19:37.070 --> 00:19:39.020
And then they would
distill it.

00:19:39.020 --> 00:19:40.940
And they would end up
with their peasant

00:19:40.940 --> 00:19:42.470
spirit, which is grappa.

00:19:42.470 --> 00:19:44.040
You've heard of grappa?

00:19:44.040 --> 00:19:47.250
Grappa is made from the
byproducts of wine-making.

00:19:47.250 --> 00:19:49.340
We've all had rum, yes?

00:19:49.340 --> 00:19:53.150
Rum is a byproduct
of sugar making.

00:19:53.150 --> 00:19:54.040
They would make sugar.

00:19:54.040 --> 00:19:55.060
They would refine sugar.

00:19:55.060 --> 00:19:58.140
When you refine sugar, you end
up with a ton of molasses and

00:19:58.140 --> 00:20:01.240
a ton of sugar cane syrup, which
the rich people would

00:20:01.240 --> 00:20:05.300
just dump behind the plantations
in giant lagoons.

00:20:05.300 --> 00:20:07.720
And it would rain, and yeast
would fall in them, and it

00:20:07.720 --> 00:20:08.850
would ferment.

00:20:08.850 --> 00:20:11.210
And the peasants would take
that liquid home, and they

00:20:11.210 --> 00:20:12.500
would distill it.

00:20:12.500 --> 00:20:14.870
And they would end
up with rum.

00:20:14.870 --> 00:20:17.660
So this is the story behind
most spirits.

00:20:17.660 --> 00:20:20.270
And the reason I mention this to
you is because I want to go

00:20:20.270 --> 00:20:24.070
to Scotland now, particularly
the UK, where their spirit is

00:20:24.070 --> 00:20:26.190
based on barley.

00:20:26.190 --> 00:20:28.720
And they end up with a
barley distillate.

00:20:28.720 --> 00:20:30.180
And they now have
to store this.

00:20:30.180 --> 00:20:31.410
And what are they going
to store it in?

00:20:31.410 --> 00:20:33.490
Well, they're going to store it
in whatever the rich people

00:20:33.490 --> 00:20:36.110
are done using, which
is wine barrels.

00:20:36.110 --> 00:20:39.890
And in Scotland in particular,
it was sherry barrels.

00:20:39.890 --> 00:20:42.720
Because all of the nobles
were drinking sherry.

00:20:42.720 --> 00:20:44.890
So they would take their raw
distillate and put it in

00:20:44.890 --> 00:20:47.610
sherry barrels, take
it out two or three

00:20:47.610 --> 00:20:49.090
or four years later.

00:20:49.090 --> 00:20:52.760
And lo and behold, it turned
into an amazing, amazing

00:20:52.760 --> 00:20:56.090
elixir that they called
Scotch whisky.

00:20:56.090 --> 00:20:57.790
Or in that corner, it was
just calling it whisky.

00:20:57.790 --> 00:20:58.960
There was no other whisky.

00:20:58.960 --> 00:20:59.990
It was just whisky.

00:20:59.990 --> 00:21:02.810
And to this day, if you go to
Scotland and you order whisky,

00:21:02.810 --> 00:21:03.730
you don't order scotch.

00:21:03.730 --> 00:21:05.310
You order whisky, right?

00:21:05.310 --> 00:21:09.680
So, barrels were traditionally
used for wines.

00:21:09.680 --> 00:21:14.440
Once you put the alcohol in
the barrel, that ethanol

00:21:14.440 --> 00:21:18.490
starts to dissolve really,
really great stuff

00:21:18.490 --> 00:21:19.740
that's in the wood.

00:21:19.740 --> 00:21:22.320
Starts to dissolve some of the
sugars in the wood, starts to

00:21:22.320 --> 00:21:24.980
dissolve some the chemicals in
the wood, things like lignins,

00:21:24.980 --> 00:21:26.720
which taste like vanilla.

00:21:26.720 --> 00:21:29.190
Starts to dissolve some of
the caramels in the wood.

00:21:29.190 --> 00:21:32.420
And all of those things
marry with the

00:21:32.420 --> 00:21:34.450
spirit over the course--

00:21:34.450 --> 00:21:36.620
ah, thank you for keeping
an eye on that.

00:21:36.620 --> 00:21:40.080
All of those things marry with
the spirit over the course of

00:21:40.080 --> 00:21:46.650
many, many years and end up
mellowing that alcohol and

00:21:46.650 --> 00:21:50.130
turning it into this whisky
that we love so much.

00:21:50.130 --> 00:21:51.750
So here's a cooperage.

00:21:51.750 --> 00:21:54.340
People who make barrels
are called coopers.

00:21:54.340 --> 00:21:57.250
This was taken just
a month or so ago.

00:21:57.250 --> 00:21:58.590
And this is all in Scotland.

00:21:58.590 --> 00:22:02.390
So you can age whisky
now in any number of

00:22:02.390 --> 00:22:04.760
different types of casks.

00:22:04.760 --> 00:22:07.150
And I want you to start
using the word cask.

00:22:07.150 --> 00:22:09.230
Barrel is not the right word.

00:22:09.230 --> 00:22:12.020
Cask is the word that we use.

00:22:12.020 --> 00:22:15.410
A barrel is actually a specific
size of cask.

00:22:15.410 --> 00:22:17.440
It's the most common size.

00:22:17.440 --> 00:22:21.300
But cask is actually the
correct technical term.

00:22:21.300 --> 00:22:25.430
French oak is mostly
used in Europe.

00:22:25.430 --> 00:22:26.890
Oak is all we use, by the way.

00:22:26.890 --> 00:22:29.250
Oak is the only thing that
you can age spirits in.

00:22:29.250 --> 00:22:31.060
We've tried every other
type of wood.

00:22:31.060 --> 00:22:33.020
Nothing works like oak.

00:22:33.020 --> 00:22:35.510
French oak is mostly used in
Europe, and it imparts a

00:22:35.510 --> 00:22:38.700
distinctive vanilla character
to the spirit.

00:22:38.700 --> 00:22:41.440
American oak imparts
more of a caramel

00:22:41.440 --> 00:22:43.660
character to the spirit.

00:22:43.660 --> 00:22:46.750
In addition to that now, I
mentioned that these whiskies

00:22:46.750 --> 00:22:51.210
were aged in casks that were
used for other things by the

00:22:51.210 --> 00:22:52.140
wealthy people.

00:22:52.140 --> 00:22:54.760
And in Scotland,
usually sherry.

00:22:54.760 --> 00:22:57.800
They didn't have the luxury
of buying brand new casks.

00:22:57.800 --> 00:22:59.080
These were peasants.

00:22:59.080 --> 00:23:02.100
You used whatever happened
to be around.

00:23:02.100 --> 00:23:04.830
So in Scotland, they were
using sherry casks.

00:23:04.830 --> 00:23:09.630
That imparts a spicy character
to the whisky.

00:23:09.630 --> 00:23:11.850
We now don't use sherry casks.

00:23:11.850 --> 00:23:15.610
Most scotch is actually
aged in bourbon casks.

00:23:15.610 --> 00:23:17.910
Because that's what we
have the most of.

00:23:17.910 --> 00:23:21.380
So the vast majority of scotch
in the world is aged in Jim

00:23:21.380 --> 00:23:24.630
Beam and Jack Daniels casks.

00:23:24.630 --> 00:23:27.600
Because that's, again,
what we have.

00:23:27.600 --> 00:23:31.110
That imparts more of a sweet
character to the whisky.

00:23:31.110 --> 00:23:35.570
So if you taste scotch today
aged in bourbon casks, it's

00:23:35.570 --> 00:23:39.630
significantly different from
scotch produced about 50 years

00:23:39.630 --> 00:23:42.500
ago that's aged in
sherry casks.

00:23:42.500 --> 00:23:46.590
And if you want to taste the
difference, taste pretty much

00:23:46.590 --> 00:23:49.320
any scotch that you buy is
going to be bourbon.

00:23:49.320 --> 00:23:51.690
But then buy Macallan.

00:23:51.690 --> 00:23:53.880
Macallan, to this day,
is still aged

00:23:53.880 --> 00:23:56.430
in 100% sherry casks.

00:23:56.430 --> 00:23:58.870
So Macallan will give you a
really good idea of what

00:23:58.870 --> 00:24:02.580
traditional sherry-aged scotch
will taste like.

00:24:02.580 --> 00:24:05.740
And it is noticeably darker
and noticeably more spicy.

00:24:11.260 --> 00:24:14.230
A couple of examples
of cask sizes.

00:24:14.230 --> 00:24:17.170
I'd mentioned that just really
briefly I want to touch on

00:24:17.170 --> 00:24:19.220
what this means.

00:24:19.220 --> 00:24:22.080
I want you to think now in
terms of surface area.

00:24:22.080 --> 00:24:25.310
If I have a very, very large
cask, I'm going to have much

00:24:25.310 --> 00:24:29.260
less reaction with the wood for
a given amount of time.

00:24:29.260 --> 00:24:34.630
So as I am creating whiskies
now, I can actually determine

00:24:34.630 --> 00:24:37.860
how much effect the wood is
going to have on the whisky by

00:24:37.860 --> 00:24:40.240
the size of the cask
that I use.

00:24:40.240 --> 00:24:42.910
So if I age my whisky in a very
small cask, I'm going to

00:24:42.910 --> 00:24:45.310
have much more interaction
with the wood.

00:24:45.310 --> 00:24:47.630
If I age my whisky in a large
cask, I'm going to have much

00:24:47.630 --> 00:24:49.340
less interaction
with the wood.

00:24:49.340 --> 00:24:52.870
I can age some whisky in large,
some whisky in small,

00:24:52.870 --> 00:24:54.240
and blend them.

00:24:54.240 --> 00:24:57.410
I can age whisky in
a small cask for a

00:24:57.410 --> 00:24:58.680
short period of time.

00:24:58.680 --> 00:25:01.050
I can age whisky in
a large cask for a

00:25:01.050 --> 00:25:02.400
long period of time.

00:25:02.400 --> 00:25:06.020
I can control a whole bunch of
different variables just based

00:25:06.020 --> 00:25:07.270
on the size of the cask.

00:25:09.870 --> 00:25:13.380
I also will char the
inside of the cask.

00:25:13.380 --> 00:25:14.620
That does two things.

00:25:14.620 --> 00:25:17.560
One, it removes some of
the character from

00:25:17.560 --> 00:25:19.280
the previous fill.

00:25:19.280 --> 00:25:21.230
Whatever was in the cask,
some of that will

00:25:21.230 --> 00:25:22.750
be removed by charring.

00:25:22.750 --> 00:25:25.060
The other thing it does
is it caramelizes the

00:25:25.060 --> 00:25:26.930
sugars in the wood.

00:25:26.930 --> 00:25:28.450
OK, so any of you guys cook?

00:25:28.450 --> 00:25:30.150
Who are my cooks here
in the room?

00:25:30.150 --> 00:25:31.060
Yeah.

00:25:31.060 --> 00:25:32.300
You brown onions, right?

00:25:32.300 --> 00:25:34.030
We've all caramelized onions.

00:25:34.030 --> 00:25:36.510
They actually turn
brown, right?

00:25:36.510 --> 00:25:37.610
We've made caramel.

00:25:37.610 --> 00:25:38.690
You take white sugar.

00:25:38.690 --> 00:25:40.420
You heat it up, and
it turns brown.

00:25:40.420 --> 00:25:42.470
That's called the Maillard
reaction.

00:25:42.470 --> 00:25:45.900
That actually breaks complex
sugars down into simple

00:25:45.900 --> 00:25:49.880
sugars, easier to digest so
they taste sweeter to us.

00:25:49.880 --> 00:25:51.480
And that's what we're doing
with this cask,

00:25:51.480 --> 00:25:52.710
the exact same thing.

00:25:52.710 --> 00:25:58.880
So when I add something like
alcohol to the cask, it's now

00:25:58.880 --> 00:26:02.380
going to dissolve those sugars
and incorporate those sugars

00:26:02.380 --> 00:26:04.050
into the spirit.

00:26:04.050 --> 00:26:04.370
AUDIENCE: You're getting
some dripping.

00:26:04.370 --> 00:26:05.600
ANTHONY CAPORALE: What?

00:26:05.600 --> 00:26:06.630
Thank you.

00:26:06.630 --> 00:26:08.860
You guys are good.

00:26:08.860 --> 00:26:10.900
And I'm going to keep
track of this.

00:26:10.900 --> 00:26:12.870
So are we impressed with
fermentation, guys?

00:26:12.870 --> 00:26:13.580
I mean, how's that?

00:26:13.580 --> 00:26:14.550
For like, what--

00:26:14.550 --> 00:26:15.780
15, 20 minutes?

00:26:15.780 --> 00:26:16.970
It's as simple as that.

00:26:16.970 --> 00:26:19.300
And believe it or not, there are
college kids all over the

00:26:19.300 --> 00:26:22.470
country that are doing this
right now in their fridge.

00:26:22.470 --> 00:26:26.110
You can literally take cider,
and you can put yeast in the

00:26:26.110 --> 00:26:28.370
cider, and they put a
balloon on top just

00:26:28.370 --> 00:26:29.380
to make an air lock.

00:26:29.380 --> 00:26:31.120
They don't need to,
but they do.

00:26:31.120 --> 00:26:34.920
And you will end up with
drinkable dry cider after

00:26:34.920 --> 00:26:35.790
about three days.

00:26:35.790 --> 00:26:38.530
And remember, the beautiful
thing about fermentation and

00:26:38.530 --> 00:26:42.250
alcoholic beverages in general,
they're difficult to

00:26:42.250 --> 00:26:43.360
make taste well.

00:26:43.360 --> 00:26:45.570
It's difficult to make
beer taste good.

00:26:45.570 --> 00:26:48.560
It's impossible to make a
fermented beverage that will

00:26:48.560 --> 00:26:51.170
harm you unless you drink
too much of it.

00:26:51.170 --> 00:26:54.510
But other than that, it
will be safe to drink.

00:26:54.510 --> 00:26:59.410
And believe it or not, it will
be safer to drink than the

00:26:59.410 --> 00:27:03.690
local water supply if we're
anywhere outside of a few

00:27:03.690 --> 00:27:05.600
years hundred years
from today.

00:27:05.600 --> 00:27:08.030
You're safer drinking a
fermented beverage than you

00:27:08.030 --> 00:27:10.990
would be drinking from the
river, stream, or well.

00:27:10.990 --> 00:27:11.980
All right?

00:27:11.980 --> 00:27:13.360
Really, really simple stuff.

00:27:13.360 --> 00:27:15.490
So let's see what we have
going on right here.

00:27:18.700 --> 00:27:19.950
My handy dandy torch.

00:27:25.030 --> 00:27:25.756
Good?

00:27:25.756 --> 00:27:28.540
Can we see this?

00:27:28.540 --> 00:27:29.640
Yes?

00:27:29.640 --> 00:27:32.244
OK.

00:27:32.244 --> 00:27:35.540
And that, folks, is
as difficult as

00:27:35.540 --> 00:27:36.810
distillation gets.

00:27:36.810 --> 00:27:39.610
So what I've done right in front
of you within the space

00:27:39.610 --> 00:27:42.330
of about, what, 30 minutes,
is we've gone

00:27:42.330 --> 00:27:44.660
from honey and yeast.

00:27:44.660 --> 00:27:48.270
The only thing I skipped is I
took this and put it in a can.

00:27:48.270 --> 00:27:50.520
But other than that, it was
the exact same thing.

00:27:50.520 --> 00:27:54.590
Honey and yeast right
down to moonshine.

00:27:54.590 --> 00:27:57.970
If I then put this in wood,
I end up with whisky.

00:27:57.970 --> 00:28:01.580
So you've seen the whole
process, very, very low tech,

00:28:01.580 --> 00:28:04.430
stuff that's been going
on for centuries.

00:28:04.430 --> 00:28:05.760
OK, we can have--

00:28:05.760 --> 00:28:09.500
getting back to the cask--
different levels of cask char.

00:28:09.500 --> 00:28:13.610
The longer you char the cask,
the darker the roast.

00:28:13.610 --> 00:28:15.140
And it's the same like coffee.

00:28:15.140 --> 00:28:17.930
You end up with more caramel,
more sugars.

00:28:17.930 --> 00:28:22.960
Darker char gives you a darker
character to the whisky.

00:28:22.960 --> 00:28:24.790
This is what we do with
the cask after.

00:28:24.790 --> 00:28:26.040
We just put them
in warehouses.

00:28:28.850 --> 00:28:31.690
But now we come back to
the big question.

00:28:31.690 --> 00:28:35.530
And this is really what makes
scotch so interesting to me.

00:28:35.530 --> 00:28:38.110
Where is the sugar
in barley, folks?

00:28:38.110 --> 00:28:40.020
We've all had--

00:28:40.020 --> 00:28:42.440
many of us probably have not had
barley, but we've all had

00:28:42.440 --> 00:28:43.520
things that are similar
to barley.

00:28:43.520 --> 00:28:44.370
We've had granola.

00:28:44.370 --> 00:28:45.720
We've had cereal.

00:28:45.720 --> 00:28:45.910
Right?

00:28:45.910 --> 00:28:49.780
We don't generally think
of grains as being

00:28:49.780 --> 00:28:51.370
particularly sweet.

00:28:51.370 --> 00:28:55.130
And we know that in order for
fermentation to happen, we

00:28:55.130 --> 00:28:56.830
have to have sugar.

00:28:56.830 --> 00:28:59.320
That's what yeast consumes.

00:28:59.320 --> 00:29:01.220
And it has to be in solution.

00:29:01.220 --> 00:29:02.670
We can't just have
a pile of sugar.

00:29:02.670 --> 00:29:04.180
It's got to be in
water, right?

00:29:04.180 --> 00:29:06.600
Which is why I did this.

00:29:06.600 --> 00:29:10.190
So where is the sugar
in barley?

00:29:10.190 --> 00:29:11.770
There isn't much.

00:29:11.770 --> 00:29:15.410
Barley is a seed.

00:29:15.410 --> 00:29:17.830
I think seeds, in general,
are amazing.

00:29:17.830 --> 00:29:23.940
Seeds are basically little
lifeboats for baby plants.

00:29:23.940 --> 00:29:24.200
Right?

00:29:24.200 --> 00:29:24.740
That's what they are.

00:29:24.740 --> 00:29:26.460
They're lifeboats
for baby plants.

00:29:26.460 --> 00:29:29.580
And we have found seeds in
Egyptian tombs, believe it or

00:29:29.580 --> 00:29:33.550
not, that we can then plant
and get to germinate.

00:29:33.550 --> 00:29:36.800
That's how good seeds
are at preserving

00:29:36.800 --> 00:29:39.540
the baby plant inside.

00:29:39.540 --> 00:29:42.750
But there's a trick that they
have to use in order to be so

00:29:42.750 --> 00:29:44.180
good at this.

00:29:44.180 --> 00:29:45.840
We consume sugar.

00:29:45.840 --> 00:29:49.050
Life consumes sugar,
including plants.

00:29:49.050 --> 00:29:51.730
That plant needs
sugar to grow.

00:29:51.730 --> 00:29:55.730
But if the mother plant were
to just surround the baby

00:29:55.730 --> 00:29:59.370
plant with sugar, guess
what would happen?

00:29:59.370 --> 00:30:00.650
Yeast would eat it.

00:30:00.650 --> 00:30:02.190
Everything would eat it.

00:30:02.190 --> 00:30:07.225
It would never end up being in
a tomb for 2,000 years and

00:30:07.225 --> 00:30:08.610
then be able to germinate.

00:30:08.610 --> 00:30:10.220
So plants came up with
a cool trick.

00:30:10.220 --> 00:30:13.060
They took the sugar, and they
said, we're going to change

00:30:13.060 --> 00:30:14.850
the form of the sugar
just a little bit.

00:30:14.850 --> 00:30:17.640
And we're going to turn it into
something called starch,

00:30:17.640 --> 00:30:18.890
which is a carbohydrate.

00:30:18.890 --> 00:30:20.210
We're going to turn
it into starch.

00:30:20.210 --> 00:30:27.410
Starch, now, actually, is
something that if you're

00:30:27.410 --> 00:30:29.230
yeast, you can't act on.

00:30:29.230 --> 00:30:32.260
So starch is something that
you can surround the plant

00:30:32.260 --> 00:30:36.400
with, and nothing else will be
able to eat that starch.

00:30:36.400 --> 00:30:40.280
Unfortunately, the plant
can't eat it either.

00:30:40.280 --> 00:30:42.990
Before the plant can use
it, it has to be

00:30:42.990 --> 00:30:45.530
converted back to sugar.

00:30:45.530 --> 00:30:47.390
So the mother plant
does two things.

00:30:47.390 --> 00:30:49.190
One, it surrounds the baby
plant with starch.

00:30:49.190 --> 00:30:52.686
And two, it puts a little enzyme
packet in the seed.

00:30:52.686 --> 00:30:55.610
And that enzyme packet
is activated

00:30:55.610 --> 00:30:58.470
when the seed is planted.

00:30:58.470 --> 00:31:01.200
When you plant the seed, the
enzyme packet breaks open,

00:31:01.200 --> 00:31:04.390
converts the starch into sugar,
and the plant can now

00:31:04.390 --> 00:31:08.690
use it in order to grow until
it breaks the ground and can

00:31:08.690 --> 00:31:10.100
start photosynthesis.

00:31:10.100 --> 00:31:13.890
But how does the seed know
when it's been planted?

00:31:13.890 --> 00:31:15.940
When it gets wet.

00:31:15.940 --> 00:31:18.820
That's the signal,
when it gets wet.

00:31:18.820 --> 00:31:23.790
So if I have barley, which is
essentially starch, but I want

00:31:23.790 --> 00:31:27.600
to convert that starch into
sugar so that I can ferment

00:31:27.600 --> 00:31:32.340
it, what I have to do is trick
that barley into thinking it's

00:31:32.340 --> 00:31:34.010
been planted.

00:31:34.010 --> 00:31:39.200
So what we do is we lay
it out on a floor,

00:31:39.200 --> 00:31:41.280
and we wet it down.

00:31:44.080 --> 00:31:47.300
When we wet it down, that enzyme
starts to react with

00:31:47.300 --> 00:31:51.170
the starch, converts the starch
into sugar, and the

00:31:51.170 --> 00:31:53.220
baby plant begins to grow.

00:31:53.220 --> 00:31:55.430
This is called malting.

00:31:55.430 --> 00:31:58.870
And if you've heard the term
malted barley or malt, that's

00:31:58.870 --> 00:32:00.260
what they're talking about.

00:32:00.260 --> 00:32:04.020
Once that baby plant starts to
grow, we know the starch has

00:32:04.020 --> 00:32:08.560
been converted into sugar, and
we need to then stop that

00:32:08.560 --> 00:32:09.635
conversion.

00:32:09.635 --> 00:32:13.950
And we do that by reversing the
process that started it.

00:32:13.950 --> 00:32:16.730
We dry the barley out.

00:32:16.730 --> 00:32:18.500
And we do that by generally
lighting low

00:32:18.500 --> 00:32:20.070
fires under the barley.

00:32:20.070 --> 00:32:21.560
It will dry the barley out.

00:32:21.560 --> 00:32:23.440
It will stop that process.

00:32:23.440 --> 00:32:25.470
And now, we can take
that barley.

00:32:25.470 --> 00:32:27.930
We can mash it, as
I showed you.

00:32:27.930 --> 00:32:28.940
We can ferment it.

00:32:28.940 --> 00:32:30.630
And we can distill it.

00:32:30.630 --> 00:32:34.560
So that whole process is called
malting, and that is

00:32:34.560 --> 00:32:37.210
what ends up giving scotch
it's really, really

00:32:37.210 --> 00:32:38.670
distinctive character.

00:32:38.670 --> 00:32:43.570
Because in order to dry the
barley, we have to, as I

00:32:43.570 --> 00:32:45.950
mentioned, light
fires under it.

00:32:45.950 --> 00:32:48.760
And in Scotland, they don't
have a lot of wood.

00:32:48.760 --> 00:32:52.060
What they do have
is peat moss.

00:32:52.060 --> 00:32:56.910
And peat moss has a very
distinctive aroma.

00:32:56.910 --> 00:33:00.180
I'm going to pass
it out for you.

00:33:00.180 --> 00:33:02.750
Go ahead and pass that around
the room, and just nose that.

00:33:02.750 --> 00:33:05.860
And that is the aroma
of peat moss.

00:33:08.710 --> 00:33:14.110
That aroma from drying the
barley, that smoke character,

00:33:14.110 --> 00:33:17.890
ends up staying with the whisky
through the grinding

00:33:17.890 --> 00:33:20.560
process, through the washing
process, through the

00:33:20.560 --> 00:33:24.190
fermentation, through the
distillation, through the

00:33:24.190 --> 00:33:29.430
aging in wood for up to 25, 30
years, and into the bottle.

00:33:29.430 --> 00:33:33.620
And we still don't understand
how that smoke character ends

00:33:33.620 --> 00:33:36.750
up lasting through that whole
process, but it does.

00:33:36.750 --> 00:33:38.700
And it's really, really
amazing to me.

00:33:38.700 --> 00:33:41.060
And it's one of the things, as
I said, that makes scotch so

00:33:41.060 --> 00:33:42.050
interesting.

00:33:42.050 --> 00:33:45.750
And it's really important that
we understand why this malting

00:33:45.750 --> 00:33:47.830
process is necessary.

00:33:47.830 --> 00:33:56.250
And it's all about making that
sugar accessible to the

00:33:56.250 --> 00:34:02.100
distiller before it was
accessible to anything else.

00:34:02.100 --> 00:34:05.460
Because if that plant was
surrounded by sugar, it would

00:34:05.460 --> 00:34:08.469
never be able to survive
as a seed.

00:34:08.469 --> 00:34:09.760
Make sense?

00:34:09.760 --> 00:34:10.920
OK.

00:34:10.920 --> 00:34:17.630
So here we have what I call
the magic of malting.

00:34:17.630 --> 00:34:19.650
So to produce ethanol from
grains, you have to convert

00:34:19.650 --> 00:34:22.620
the starch back to ferment-able
sugars through

00:34:22.620 --> 00:34:25.360
the process called malting.

00:34:25.360 --> 00:34:29.880
This is starch and water, yields
maltose, which is a

00:34:29.880 --> 00:34:33.560
form of sugar that we use
to ferment, and oxygen.

00:34:33.560 --> 00:34:35.989
That's the malting equation.

00:34:35.989 --> 00:34:38.500
Grains are made to germinate
by soaking in water, which

00:34:38.500 --> 00:34:39.639
develop the enzymes.

00:34:39.639 --> 00:34:44.770
This is called modifying the
starch back into sugars.

00:34:44.770 --> 00:34:49.960
And this is the process that
allows us essentially to form

00:34:49.960 --> 00:34:52.489
the spirit industry.

00:34:52.489 --> 00:34:55.429
The maltose that we produce is
then broken down into fructose

00:34:55.429 --> 00:34:56.540
and glucose.

00:34:56.540 --> 00:34:59.830
Yeast can then convert those
fructose and glucose molecules

00:34:59.830 --> 00:35:01.826
into ethanol and carbon dioxide
through fermentation.

00:35:04.560 --> 00:35:05.810
Here's your equation.

00:35:08.680 --> 00:35:12.930
Glucose yields ethanol
and carbon dioxide.

00:35:12.930 --> 00:35:15.240
So that is essentially
the chemistry

00:35:15.240 --> 00:35:17.750
behind the spirits industry.

00:35:17.750 --> 00:35:20.745
And I say that every drop of
alcohol is essentially a ray

00:35:20.745 --> 00:35:21.940
of star shine.

00:35:21.940 --> 00:35:25.760
Because that's really where
this all comes from.

00:35:25.760 --> 00:35:28.230
Our bodies retrieve the energy
stored in the chemical bonds

00:35:28.230 --> 00:35:32.600
of ethanol through the oxidation
to acetaldehyde and

00:35:32.600 --> 00:35:33.850
finally acetal.

00:35:38.290 --> 00:35:40.670
And basically, I like to say
that's why I hate "The

00:35:40.670 --> 00:35:44.050
Matrix." Because if you
remember, in "The Matrix,"

00:35:44.050 --> 00:35:46.570
they never accounted for the
fact that energy was being put

00:35:46.570 --> 00:35:47.770
into the system.

00:35:47.770 --> 00:35:50.730
They were just constantly
harvesting people, right?

00:35:50.730 --> 00:35:54.010
You have to have energy put into
the system at some point.

00:35:54.010 --> 00:35:58.630
And it always has to start
with sunshine.

00:35:58.630 --> 00:36:01.660
So this is what floor malting
looks like, just a bunch of

00:36:01.660 --> 00:36:04.250
barley laid out over
the floor.

00:36:04.250 --> 00:36:05.600
This is what a peat
bog looks like.

00:36:05.600 --> 00:36:08.100
This is where we actually
harvest the peat that we'll

00:36:08.100 --> 00:36:11.610
then use to dry the malt.

00:36:11.610 --> 00:36:13.540
And this is what the malted
barley looks like.

00:36:13.540 --> 00:36:14.610
They'll actually--

00:36:14.610 --> 00:36:18.400
they can tell when to stop the
malting process by the length

00:36:18.400 --> 00:36:19.930
of those rootlets.

00:36:19.930 --> 00:36:22.950
And the master malter will
actually go through and pick

00:36:22.950 --> 00:36:25.100
up a handful of malted barley
and measure the

00:36:25.100 --> 00:36:26.120
length of the rootlets.

00:36:26.120 --> 00:36:29.000
And by the length of the
rootlets, he can tell whether

00:36:29.000 --> 00:36:31.350
or not the sugar has been
completely modified.

00:36:34.010 --> 00:36:37.890
So let's look at a summary
now, of making whisky.

00:36:37.890 --> 00:36:40.210
First, we have to harvest
the grain.

00:36:40.210 --> 00:36:41.530
Then, we have to
mill the grain.

00:36:41.530 --> 00:36:44.360
We have to crack the
shell of the grain

00:36:44.360 --> 00:36:45.770
to get to the inside.

00:36:45.770 --> 00:36:47.810
We wash it into wort.

00:36:47.810 --> 00:36:51.810
We then ferment the wort into
beer, distill the beer into

00:36:51.810 --> 00:36:52.450
new whisky.

00:36:52.450 --> 00:36:54.500
We age it into casks.

00:36:54.500 --> 00:36:58.530
At that point, we can now blend
the whisky, very, very

00:36:58.530 --> 00:36:59.570
common in the industry.

00:36:59.570 --> 00:37:01.340
We've all had Johnny
Walker, yes?

00:37:01.340 --> 00:37:02.760
We've all had Dewar's.

00:37:02.760 --> 00:37:05.500
These are all blended
whiskies.

00:37:05.500 --> 00:37:08.270
What a blended whisky is, you'll
take whisky from a

00:37:08.270 --> 00:37:11.470
number of different distillers,
a number of

00:37:11.470 --> 00:37:15.090
different ages, and you'll
blend them all together.

00:37:15.090 --> 00:37:19.070
And the idea is to produce a
consistent whisky over time.

00:37:19.070 --> 00:37:22.990
So if whisky A comes in a little
sweeter than usual,

00:37:22.990 --> 00:37:26.000
you'll maybe use a little less
of it in the blend in order to

00:37:26.000 --> 00:37:27.790
maintain a consistent profile.

00:37:27.790 --> 00:37:30.470
Next time it comes in a little
less sweet, you'll use a

00:37:30.470 --> 00:37:31.570
little more of it.

00:37:31.570 --> 00:37:34.840
But your whisky blend,
the profile, will be

00:37:34.840 --> 00:37:36.960
consistent over time.

00:37:36.960 --> 00:37:39.780
Those are called blended
whiskies.

00:37:39.780 --> 00:37:42.720
The alternative to a blended
whisky is what's called a

00:37:42.720 --> 00:37:44.050
single malt whisky.

00:37:44.050 --> 00:37:46.420
And we've all had single
malt scotches.

00:37:46.420 --> 00:37:50.510
And a single malt whisky is
a single distillery and

00:37:50.510 --> 00:37:54.530
generally a single
harvest of malt.

00:37:54.530 --> 00:37:57.320
So it's much more difficult
to maintain

00:37:57.320 --> 00:37:59.770
consistency over time.

00:37:59.770 --> 00:38:04.450
Any variation in that malted
whisky is going to show up in

00:38:04.450 --> 00:38:06.030
the end product.

00:38:06.030 --> 00:38:08.380
Whatever comes off the still,
whatever comes out of that

00:38:08.380 --> 00:38:10.860
barrel, that's what's going
to end up in the bottle.

00:38:10.860 --> 00:38:14.250
So if you're trying to make
Macallan, and you end up with

00:38:14.250 --> 00:38:18.040
a batch that doesn't quite taste
like the way Macallan

00:38:18.040 --> 00:38:21.760
used to taste, you have to sell
that batch to a blender.

00:38:21.760 --> 00:38:23.620
You can't bottle it as
Macallan because your

00:38:23.620 --> 00:38:24.920
customers are not going
to want it.

00:38:24.920 --> 00:38:26.830
They're not going to
be used to that.

00:38:26.830 --> 00:38:29.965
So single malt is a little
bit riskier to make.

00:38:34.130 --> 00:38:36.360
The peat's making its
round, the smoke?

00:38:36.360 --> 00:38:36.930
Right?

00:38:36.930 --> 00:38:39.680
Pretty intense, yes?

00:38:39.680 --> 00:38:43.800
So some of the flavors that
we're looking for in whiskies

00:38:43.800 --> 00:38:47.210
in general, obviously grain is
going to be the primary flavor

00:38:47.210 --> 00:38:48.620
in all whiskies.

00:38:48.620 --> 00:38:53.090
Cereal, sometimes described as
bran, biscuitty, malty, mashy.

00:38:53.090 --> 00:38:56.590
Wood is the next most
prominent flavor.

00:38:56.590 --> 00:38:59.870
And there are some distillers
that actually say wood is the

00:38:59.870 --> 00:39:01.610
most prominent flavor.

00:39:01.610 --> 00:39:05.190
A lot of the folks that I work
with today are saying that 60%

00:39:05.190 --> 00:39:07.780
of the flavor of any whisky
comes from the wood.

00:39:07.780 --> 00:39:09.910
And they're actually investing
a lot of money in what they

00:39:09.910 --> 00:39:12.720
call wood technology.

00:39:12.720 --> 00:39:16.310
Has anyone ever tried
Maker's 46?

00:39:16.310 --> 00:39:16.850
No?

00:39:16.850 --> 00:39:19.240
OK, so we all know Maker's
Mark, yes?

00:39:19.240 --> 00:39:21.370
Maker's Mark came out
with a new bourbon.

00:39:21.370 --> 00:39:23.260
Now, Maker's Mark
is a bourbon.

00:39:23.260 --> 00:39:25.890
They came up with a new bourbon
call Maker's 46.

00:39:25.890 --> 00:39:27.980
It was the first new product
that they'd introduced in

00:39:27.980 --> 00:39:30.210
about 55 years.

00:39:30.210 --> 00:39:33.440
Maker's 46 is what they called
it, and people can't figure

00:39:33.440 --> 00:39:35.560
out why they called
it Maker's 46.

00:39:35.560 --> 00:39:38.250
People think that it's
46 years old.

00:39:38.250 --> 00:39:41.520
People think that
it's 46 proof.

00:39:41.520 --> 00:39:46.670
46 is actually the number
of what they

00:39:46.670 --> 00:39:49.520
call the wood profile.

00:39:49.520 --> 00:39:55.430
Out of 100 different types of
wood that they tested, they

00:39:55.430 --> 00:39:57.950
ended up using the 46th.

00:39:57.950 --> 00:40:01.080
So they called Maker's
46 Maker's 46

00:40:01.080 --> 00:40:02.720
based on the wood profile.

00:40:02.720 --> 00:40:07.140
And my point here is that they
tried 100 different types of

00:40:07.140 --> 00:40:11.480
wood charred 100 different ways
before they came up with

00:40:11.480 --> 00:40:14.070
one that they felt worked.

00:40:14.070 --> 00:40:16.960
And that's the level of
investment and time that

00:40:16.960 --> 00:40:19.160
people are putting into
wood technology today.

00:40:19.160 --> 00:40:22.550
Because wood has so much
influence on the final

00:40:22.550 --> 00:40:24.340
character of the whisky.

00:40:24.340 --> 00:40:30.120
All right, so oak, cedar, nut,
marzipan, walnut-- all these

00:40:30.120 --> 00:40:32.940
things can come from wood.

00:40:32.940 --> 00:40:35.740
In addition to that, we have
what we call sweet aromatics.

00:40:35.740 --> 00:40:37.450
And that's things
like vanillas,

00:40:37.450 --> 00:40:39.050
caramels, maple syrup.

00:40:39.050 --> 00:40:41.430
Believe it or not, those also
come from the wood.

00:40:41.430 --> 00:40:44.320
And that's from the
caramelization of sugar.

00:40:44.320 --> 00:40:46.160
And then we have the
spice component.

00:40:46.160 --> 00:40:49.720
And the spice component also
comes generally from the wood.

00:40:49.720 --> 00:40:52.940
There's a little bit added by
the cereal, but most of it is

00:40:52.940 --> 00:40:54.190
from the wood.

00:40:56.470 --> 00:40:59.670
Fruit and floral, we can get
everything from cherries,

00:40:59.670 --> 00:41:02.400
oranges, blackberries,
peaches to things

00:41:02.400 --> 00:41:04.310
like rose and lavender.

00:41:04.310 --> 00:41:06.960
For Scotch and Irish whiskies,
we have peat, which you guys

00:41:06.960 --> 00:41:10.330
all just smelled and tasted, and
then the astringent notes

00:41:10.330 --> 00:41:13.560
that come from the
alcohol itself.

00:41:13.560 --> 00:41:16.790
So let's talk now a little bit
about scotch whisky in

00:41:16.790 --> 00:41:19.500
particular, so that you have
an idea of what the scotch

00:41:19.500 --> 00:41:22.040
whisky regulations are.

00:41:22.040 --> 00:41:24.220
One, in order to be called
scotch, it has

00:41:24.220 --> 00:41:25.640
to be made in Scotland.

00:41:25.640 --> 00:41:26.970
And believe it or not,
that's a revelation

00:41:26.970 --> 00:41:29.200
to some folks, right?

00:41:29.200 --> 00:41:34.080
You can't call it scotch if
it's not made in Scotland.

00:41:34.080 --> 00:41:37.910
It has to be made from malted
barley, and it has to be

00:41:37.910 --> 00:41:41.880
distilled to less than 95%.

00:41:41.880 --> 00:41:45.270
So now that you guys know a
lot about fermentation and

00:41:45.270 --> 00:41:48.190
distillation, I want you to
start thinking about-- when I

00:41:48.190 --> 00:41:51.450
say things like, it has to be
distilled to less than 95%

00:41:51.450 --> 00:41:55.710
alcohol, let's talk about
what that means.

00:41:55.710 --> 00:42:00.530
Why would they restrict the
percentage that I can

00:42:00.530 --> 00:42:01.800
distill whisky to?

00:42:01.800 --> 00:42:04.490
Why would they say I
can't distill it

00:42:04.490 --> 00:42:06.150
above a certain percent?

00:42:06.150 --> 00:42:08.794
Any thoughts on that?

00:42:08.794 --> 00:42:10.586
AUDIENCE: --the flavors.

00:42:10.586 --> 00:42:12.110
Won't you get a change in the
flavor profile, if it's 5%?

00:42:12.110 --> 00:42:13.820
ANTHONY CAPORALE: You bet.

00:42:13.820 --> 00:42:13.890
Yep.

00:42:13.890 --> 00:42:16.640
You get a change in the
flavor profile.

00:42:16.640 --> 00:42:21.660
The more pure the alcohol coming
off the still, the less

00:42:21.660 --> 00:42:25.930
character of the base grain
that comes with it.

00:42:25.930 --> 00:42:27.770
So think about that
for a second.

00:42:27.770 --> 00:42:33.190
If coming out of this still is
99% ethyl alcohol, there's

00:42:33.190 --> 00:42:36.300
almost nothing left of
the original base

00:42:36.300 --> 00:42:39.100
grain in that 99%.

00:42:39.100 --> 00:42:45.370
If I reduce that to 80%, let's
say 20% is water that comes

00:42:45.370 --> 00:42:46.880
from the base grain.

00:42:46.880 --> 00:42:48.870
And with that water is
going to be essential

00:42:48.870 --> 00:42:50.970
oils, asters, aromatics.

00:42:50.970 --> 00:42:56.480
So the lower the percent you
distill to, the more original

00:42:56.480 --> 00:42:59.700
character of the base
grain you preserve.

00:42:59.700 --> 00:43:03.860
So for a spirit like whisky
where we want that base

00:43:03.860 --> 00:43:07.200
character, we want that grain
character, you want to

00:43:07.200 --> 00:43:11.010
restrict the distillation ABV.

00:43:11.010 --> 00:43:13.560
Can you think of a spirit
where they would want to

00:43:13.560 --> 00:43:17.420
distill to a very high percent,
where they want very

00:43:17.420 --> 00:43:19.675
little of the base character?

00:43:19.675 --> 00:43:19.990
AUDIENCE: Vodka.

00:43:19.990 --> 00:43:20.750
ANTHONY CAPORALE:
You've got it.

00:43:20.750 --> 00:43:21.300
Who said vodka?

00:43:21.300 --> 00:43:22.290
Yes.

00:43:22.290 --> 00:43:23.000
Vodka.

00:43:23.000 --> 00:43:25.330
Vodka wants to be odorless,
colorless, tasteless.

00:43:25.330 --> 00:43:26.450
That's what it wants.

00:43:26.450 --> 00:43:30.060
So vodka has to be distilled to
a very, very high percent.

00:43:30.060 --> 00:43:33.720
Whisky says no, you
can't distill

00:43:33.720 --> 00:43:34.950
above a certain percent.

00:43:34.950 --> 00:43:37.570
We want that base character.

00:43:37.570 --> 00:43:38.710
OK?

00:43:38.710 --> 00:43:41.720
I mentioned pot distillation
and column

00:43:41.720 --> 00:43:43.770
distillation early on.

00:43:43.770 --> 00:43:46.300
Again, now you know enough about
distillation, I can talk

00:43:46.300 --> 00:43:47.590
about that a little bit.

00:43:47.590 --> 00:43:52.140
With a column distillation or
a continuous distillation

00:43:52.140 --> 00:43:56.030
process, I want to take
a look at what we have

00:43:56.030 --> 00:43:57.150
going on right here.

00:43:57.150 --> 00:44:02.240
With a still, if I'm doing a
batch distillation, I have

00:44:02.240 --> 00:44:05.490
water and alcohol, and
it starts to heat up.

00:44:05.490 --> 00:44:09.380
Before it gets to about 175,
there are other things in here

00:44:09.380 --> 00:44:11.350
besides water and alcohol.

00:44:11.350 --> 00:44:12.520
There are things that
come from the

00:44:12.520 --> 00:44:14.040
grain that are in there.

00:44:14.040 --> 00:44:14.960
There are oils.

00:44:14.960 --> 00:44:16.020
There are esters.

00:44:16.020 --> 00:44:18.220
There are all kinds of other
things in there.

00:44:18.220 --> 00:44:20.560
Some things good, some things
not so good, all

00:44:20.560 --> 00:44:22.240
based from the plant.

00:44:22.240 --> 00:44:27.800
Before that alcohol starts to
turn into a gas, other things

00:44:27.800 --> 00:44:32.110
start to evaporate first, things
with a lower boiling

00:44:32.110 --> 00:44:33.900
point than alcohol.

00:44:33.900 --> 00:44:36.440
We call those the heads.

00:44:36.440 --> 00:44:38.640
They have certain flavors.

00:44:38.640 --> 00:44:44.490
Then the alcohol starts to turn
into a gas and evaporate.

00:44:44.490 --> 00:44:45.860
We call that the heart.

00:44:45.860 --> 00:44:47.260
That's pure ethanol.

00:44:47.260 --> 00:44:52.040
Once the alcohol is done, other
things with a higher

00:44:52.040 --> 00:44:54.370
boiling point than the alcohol
start to evaporate.

00:44:54.370 --> 00:44:56.610
We call those the tails.

00:44:56.610 --> 00:44:58.830
And those also have
flavors and odors

00:44:58.830 --> 00:45:00.180
associated with them.

00:45:00.180 --> 00:45:02.690
What we really want
is that heart cut.

00:45:02.690 --> 00:45:04.340
We want the ethanol.

00:45:04.340 --> 00:45:07.160
But in a pot or batch
distillation, we

00:45:07.160 --> 00:45:08.850
get the heads first.

00:45:08.850 --> 00:45:10.890
Then we get the heart.

00:45:10.890 --> 00:45:13.250
And then we get the tails.

00:45:13.250 --> 00:45:18.850
The distiller can decide what
cut he's going to take.

00:45:18.850 --> 00:45:21.740
So I want you to think about a
couple things now, one from an

00:45:21.740 --> 00:45:23.610
economic standpoint.

00:45:23.610 --> 00:45:25.670
You want to take the largest
cut possible, because

00:45:25.670 --> 00:45:27.250
everything that you're not
putting in the bottle, you're

00:45:27.250 --> 00:45:29.980
throwing away, and
that's waste.

00:45:29.980 --> 00:45:31.550
So you want take the largest
cut possible.

00:45:31.550 --> 00:45:36.920
But the larger the cut you take,
the more heads and tails

00:45:36.920 --> 00:45:38.760
end up in the bottle.

00:45:38.760 --> 00:45:44.080
And that oftentimes gives
you odors and aromas

00:45:44.080 --> 00:45:46.770
that you may not want.

00:45:46.770 --> 00:45:48.590
During prohibition, for example,
we've all heard of

00:45:48.590 --> 00:45:50.130
bathtub gin, right?

00:45:50.130 --> 00:45:52.300
We know that during prohibition,
alcohol wasn't

00:45:52.300 --> 00:45:53.540
particularly high quality.

00:45:53.540 --> 00:45:56.120
Moonshine, to this day, has a
reputation for making you go

00:45:56.120 --> 00:45:57.430
blind, right?

00:45:57.430 --> 00:46:00.090
Because moonshine produced in
the mountains of West Virginia

00:46:00.090 --> 00:46:03.320
by a guy who probably doesn't
have a Ph.D. In chemistry,

00:46:03.320 --> 00:46:04.960
he's just taking the
whole thing and

00:46:04.960 --> 00:46:05.650
putting it in a bottle.

00:46:05.650 --> 00:46:07.730
He's maximizing his profits.

00:46:07.730 --> 00:46:10.030
Those heads and tails
will make you sick.

00:46:10.030 --> 00:46:10.950
They will make you blind.

00:46:10.950 --> 00:46:12.400
They're toxic.

00:46:12.400 --> 00:46:12.680
OK?

00:46:12.680 --> 00:46:17.880
They also do, however,
contribute flavors and odors

00:46:17.880 --> 00:46:20.360
to the final product.

00:46:20.360 --> 00:46:25.810
So you take too much and you
end up with off odors, off

00:46:25.810 --> 00:46:28.340
aromas, and some toxins.

00:46:28.340 --> 00:46:30.110
You take too little,
however, and you're

00:46:30.110 --> 00:46:31.790
not making any money.

00:46:31.790 --> 00:46:34.370
So there's a happy medium in
there that you have to decide

00:46:34.370 --> 00:46:36.020
on what you're going to take.

00:46:36.020 --> 00:46:39.080
That's pot distillation
or batch distillation.

00:46:39.080 --> 00:46:43.020
Column distillation, because
it's continuous, you don't

00:46:43.020 --> 00:46:44.750
have to worry about that.

00:46:44.750 --> 00:46:46.690
There's heads when
you turn it on.

00:46:46.690 --> 00:46:48.610
And then it runs for weeks.

00:46:48.610 --> 00:46:50.980
Heart, heart, heart,
heart, heart.

00:46:50.980 --> 00:46:53.160
And then tails when
you turn it off.

00:46:53.160 --> 00:46:57.850
So a column or continuous still
is a much cleaner, purer

00:46:57.850 --> 00:47:00.330
method of distilling alcohol.

00:47:00.330 --> 00:47:05.530
And believe it or not, with
whisky and scotch whisky, in

00:47:05.530 --> 00:47:10.140
particular, you're not allowed
to use column distillation for

00:47:10.140 --> 00:47:11.800
single malts.

00:47:11.800 --> 00:47:15.080
Because they don't want
it to be that clean.

00:47:15.080 --> 00:47:19.160
They want the character that's
imparted by some heads and

00:47:19.160 --> 00:47:20.500
some tails.

00:47:20.500 --> 00:47:23.120
They don't just want
pure ethyl alcohol.

00:47:23.120 --> 00:47:27.350
So a couple of interesting
things on this slide.

00:47:27.350 --> 00:47:32.350
One, we're limiting the percent
ABV for distillation

00:47:32.350 --> 00:47:33.940
in an attempt to preserve
character

00:47:33.940 --> 00:47:35.620
of those base grains.

00:47:35.620 --> 00:47:39.790
We're also saying pot stills,
baby, in an attempt to

00:47:39.790 --> 00:47:42.470
preserve the character
of those base grains.

00:47:42.470 --> 00:47:46.170
So do you see how whisky and
scotch whisky in particular,

00:47:46.170 --> 00:47:50.710
it's very, very important that
they preserve that malted

00:47:50.710 --> 00:47:55.200
barley character in the bottle
as opposed to, again, some

00:47:55.200 --> 00:47:57.910
spirits that we can talk
about like vodka,

00:47:57.910 --> 00:47:59.350
where that's not important.

00:47:59.350 --> 00:48:02.150
And this is one of, to me,
one of the really, really

00:48:02.150 --> 00:48:04.840
interesting things about whisky,
is it's all about

00:48:04.840 --> 00:48:06.600
preserving that grain
experience.

00:48:10.630 --> 00:48:12.750
Real quick, and then I'm going
to wrap up so that we can go

00:48:12.750 --> 00:48:14.980
drink, but again, I just want
you to know a little bit about

00:48:14.980 --> 00:48:17.050
some of these things
in Scotland.

00:48:17.050 --> 00:48:22.460
There are four basic regions
that produce Scotland, and

00:48:22.460 --> 00:48:24.320
then one that doesn't really
do a whole lot.

00:48:24.320 --> 00:48:26.590
We have the lowlands,
the highlands, Islay

00:48:26.590 --> 00:48:28.550
scotches, and Speyside.

00:48:28.550 --> 00:48:31.020
Campbeltown doesn't produce
a whole lot anymore.

00:48:31.020 --> 00:48:34.070
The one I want to point out for
the average person-- or

00:48:34.070 --> 00:48:34.970
the two, actually--

00:48:34.970 --> 00:48:37.570
Islay and Speyside.

00:48:37.570 --> 00:48:42.240
So Islay scotch, if you like
that peat aroma, if you like

00:48:42.240 --> 00:48:44.700
that smoke that I passed
out, you want

00:48:44.700 --> 00:48:47.520
to drink Islay scotches.

00:48:47.520 --> 00:48:47.790
All right?

00:48:47.790 --> 00:48:48.960
You may want to write
that down.

00:48:48.960 --> 00:48:50.570
It is pronounced Islay.

00:48:50.570 --> 00:48:54.080
And Islay scotches are known for
producing very peaty, very

00:48:54.080 --> 00:48:56.090
smoky scotches.

00:48:56.090 --> 00:49:00.290
Speyside is the largest
region--

00:49:00.290 --> 00:49:01.560
not the largest geographically--

00:49:01.560 --> 00:49:04.270
they produce the most scotches
and they produce generally

00:49:04.270 --> 00:49:06.810
what's considered to be the
classic scotch whisky.

00:49:06.810 --> 00:49:10.150
So if you want to get started on
very classic malt scotches,

00:49:10.150 --> 00:49:12.220
look for Speyside scotches.

00:49:12.220 --> 00:49:14.300
And we're actually going to
taste you, when we go

00:49:14.300 --> 00:49:17.220
upstairs, we're going to taste
