00:49:17.220 --> 00:49:19.050
Speyside malt.

00:49:19.050 --> 00:49:20.210
OK?

00:49:20.210 --> 00:49:22.180
Any questions?

00:49:22.180 --> 00:49:22.850
No?

00:49:22.850 --> 00:49:23.275
Yes.

00:49:23.275 --> 00:49:26.940
AUDIENCE: Why is it always the
same years, like 12, 15?

00:49:26.940 --> 00:49:28.030
ANTHONY CAPORALE:
Great question.

00:49:28.030 --> 00:49:32.040
So the question was, why do you
always see the same years

00:49:32.040 --> 00:49:32.880
on the bottle?

00:49:32.880 --> 00:49:37.340
One thing about years, know that
the year is the youngest

00:49:37.340 --> 00:49:38.970
scotch in the bottle, by law.

00:49:38.970 --> 00:49:42.400
So if the bottle says 12, there
may be older scotches in

00:49:42.400 --> 00:49:45.870
that bottle, but there can't be
anything younger than 12 in

00:49:45.870 --> 00:49:46.960
the bottle.

00:49:46.960 --> 00:49:50.950
Convention has said that we're
going to bottle scotch at 6

00:49:50.950 --> 00:49:56.620
years, 8 years, 12 years, and
15 years, just convention.

00:49:56.620 --> 00:49:58.850
You'll see scotches
bottled at 17.

00:49:58.850 --> 00:50:01.140
You'll see scotches
bottled at 25.

00:50:01.140 --> 00:50:03.360
It's just a convention that
the industry has sort of

00:50:03.360 --> 00:50:05.510
adopted over time.

00:50:05.510 --> 00:50:07.100
Anything else?

00:50:07.100 --> 00:50:07.385
Yes?

00:50:07.385 --> 00:50:09.220
AUDIENCE: How does
sour mash work?

00:50:09.220 --> 00:50:13.250
ANTHONY CAPORALE: Sour mash
is an American tradition.

00:50:13.250 --> 00:50:16.000
And sour mash is what they
use for bourbons

00:50:16.000 --> 00:50:17.570
and Tennessee whisky.

00:50:17.570 --> 00:50:21.830
And all sour mash means is
that they use a starter.

00:50:21.830 --> 00:50:23.150
Anyone bake bread here?

00:50:23.150 --> 00:50:26.430
Do I have any bread bakers?

00:50:26.430 --> 00:50:28.470
You know sourdough bread?

00:50:28.470 --> 00:50:32.770
Sourdough bread is
always started by

00:50:32.770 --> 00:50:34.840
the same yeast strain.

00:50:34.840 --> 00:50:38.930
They'll actually preserve the
yeast from batch to batch, and

00:50:38.930 --> 00:50:41.250
they will seed the next batch
with the yeast from it.

00:50:41.250 --> 00:50:44.860
Because yeast is really what
contributes most of the flavor

00:50:44.860 --> 00:50:45.610
to these things.

00:50:45.610 --> 00:50:50.590
And sour mash just means that
they will seed it with a batch

00:50:50.590 --> 00:50:53.680
from the previous distillation
or fermentation, rather.

00:50:53.680 --> 00:50:54.140
Yeah?

00:50:54.140 --> 00:50:56.900
AUDIENCE: You said earlier
bourbon is whisky, but you

00:50:56.900 --> 00:50:59.770
also can also age whisky
in bourbon casks.

00:50:59.770 --> 00:51:00.145
ANTHONY CAPORALE: Yes.

00:51:00.145 --> 00:51:02.270
AUDIENCE: Are you just reusing
the cask repeatedly?

00:51:02.270 --> 00:51:02.750
ANTHONY CAPORALE: Yes.

00:51:02.750 --> 00:51:06.030
So bourbon whisky now, in order
to be called bourbon,

00:51:06.030 --> 00:51:09.110
you have to be made in
the United States,

00:51:09.110 --> 00:51:12.180
as opposed to Scotland.

00:51:12.180 --> 00:51:13.570
Not Bourbon County, folks.

00:51:13.570 --> 00:51:15.290
It just is the United States.

00:51:15.290 --> 00:51:18.120
And the base grain in
bourbon is corn.

00:51:18.120 --> 00:51:19.200
Because that's our base grain.

00:51:19.200 --> 00:51:20.970
That's what we have here
in this country.

00:51:20.970 --> 00:51:23.010
So bourbon is a whisky.

00:51:23.010 --> 00:51:27.320
Bourbon has to be made
in new casks by law.

00:51:27.320 --> 00:51:30.480
You don't make bourbon in
a cask that was used for

00:51:30.480 --> 00:51:31.450
something else.

00:51:31.450 --> 00:51:34.820
Brand new American oak casks.

00:51:34.820 --> 00:51:37.710
So when you're done making the
bourbon, you only have two

00:51:37.710 --> 00:51:39.180
things you can do
with that cask.

00:51:39.180 --> 00:51:43.550
You can throw it out, or you can
sell it to a scotch whisky

00:51:43.550 --> 00:51:45.420
manufacturer.

00:51:45.420 --> 00:51:49.014
Because bourbon can only
use new casks.

00:51:49.014 --> 00:51:50.942
AUDIENCE: Did you have to get
some kind of license to

00:51:50.942 --> 00:51:52.388
operate that still?

00:51:55.220 --> 00:51:58.360
ANTHONY CAPORALE: If it's bigger
than one gallon, which

00:51:58.360 --> 00:52:01.870
this is not, or if it's not
being used in a laboratory or

00:52:01.870 --> 00:52:04.530
educational setting, then you
need to have a distilling

00:52:04.530 --> 00:52:05.790
license to operate it.

