AUDIENCE: So, [INAUDIBLE]
a laboratory

00:52:07.078 --> 00:52:10.042
or educational setting.

00:52:10.042 --> 00:52:12.018
What's considered a laboratory
or [INAUDIBLE]

00:52:12.018 --> 00:52:13.006
educational setting?

00:52:13.006 --> 00:52:13.500
[LAUGHTER]

00:52:13.500 --> 00:52:14.990
ANTHONY CAPORALE: It's
a good question.

00:52:14.990 --> 00:52:16.240
You probably don't have one.

00:52:19.500 --> 00:52:20.845
You probably don't have one.

00:52:20.845 --> 00:52:22.165
This would be considered
a laboratory

00:52:22.165 --> 00:52:23.250
or educational setting.

00:52:23.250 --> 00:52:24.550
A school would be considered
a laboratory

00:52:24.550 --> 00:52:25.610
or educational setting.

00:52:25.610 --> 00:52:28.040
A laboratory would be considered
a laboratory or

00:52:28.040 --> 00:52:31.074
educational setting.

00:52:31.074 --> 00:52:33.020
AUDIENCE: What about
filtration?

00:52:33.020 --> 00:52:34.045
ANTHONY CAPORALE:
Filtration of--

00:52:34.045 --> 00:52:36.220
AUDIENCE: Of scotch,
do they do that?

00:52:36.220 --> 00:52:37.790
ANTHONY CAPORALE: Yeah, so--

00:52:37.790 --> 00:52:39.510
in other words, do they do
it, how do they do it.

00:52:39.510 --> 00:52:40.360
AUDIENCE: They do something
that's like filters,

00:52:40.360 --> 00:52:41.750
[INAUDIBLE] talk about.

00:52:41.750 --> 00:52:42.260
ANTHONY CAPORALE: I'm sorry?

00:52:42.260 --> 00:52:42.680
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:52:42.680 --> 00:52:44.870
They'll talk about that as
a sort of evil thing.

00:52:44.870 --> 00:52:45.300
ANTHONY CAPORALE: Yeah.

00:52:45.300 --> 00:52:49.530
So filtration, there's two
theories of filtration.

00:52:49.530 --> 00:52:52.250
One is that it's totally fine,
and it's a good thing because

00:52:52.250 --> 00:52:53.220
it clarifies the liquid.

00:52:53.220 --> 00:52:55.580
And two is that it completely
ruins the scotch, and don't

00:52:55.580 --> 00:52:56.840
ever do it, right?

00:52:56.840 --> 00:53:00.190
So all we're trying to do with
filtration is remove solid

00:53:00.190 --> 00:53:01.890
particulates from the scotch.

00:53:01.890 --> 00:53:02.980
And there are a bunch
of different ways

00:53:02.980 --> 00:53:03.510
that they do it.

00:53:03.510 --> 00:53:04.330
They can add pectin.

00:53:04.330 --> 00:53:06.770
They can do chill filtration.

00:53:06.770 --> 00:53:10.140
I personally think that it will
remove a little bit of

00:53:10.140 --> 00:53:12.420
the character from the scotch.

00:53:12.420 --> 00:53:14.870
But I've had tons and tons
of filtered scotches.

00:53:14.870 --> 00:53:17.180
Most of the scotches that we've
all had in our lives

00:53:17.180 --> 00:53:19.090
have been filtered, and
they're delicious.

00:53:19.090 --> 00:53:20.560
There's nothing wrong with it.

00:53:20.560 --> 00:53:23.470
But the scotch purists will tell
you that they're not fans

00:53:23.470 --> 00:53:24.720
of filtered scotch.

00:53:26.830 --> 00:53:30.810
AUDIENCE: Do you know what
causes the flavors from the

00:53:30.810 --> 00:53:33.070
grain, is it the water, or the
barley, or is it the mixture?

00:53:33.070 --> 00:53:34.124
ANTHONY CAPORALE: I'm sorry?

00:53:34.124 --> 00:53:35.606
AUDIENCE: What causes the
different flavors, depending

00:53:35.606 --> 00:53:37.900
on where it is in Scotland?

00:53:37.900 --> 00:53:38.260
ANTHONY CAPORALE: Yes.

00:53:38.260 --> 00:53:41.330
What causes the different
flavors, really, really good.

00:53:41.330 --> 00:53:43.610
So, let's go to the map.

00:53:47.120 --> 00:53:48.720
So this is our scotch regions.

00:53:48.720 --> 00:53:49.740
This is the Highlands.

00:53:49.740 --> 00:53:51.120
This is Speyside.

00:53:51.120 --> 00:53:54.810
This is the Lowlands,
Campbeltown, and Islay.

00:53:54.810 --> 00:53:58.740
So Islay, you can see are
all island regions.

00:53:58.740 --> 00:54:01.920
So what causes the flavor that's
characteristic to the

00:54:01.920 --> 00:54:05.420
Islay scotches is one, peat.

00:54:05.420 --> 00:54:06.870
There are no forests
on the coast.

00:54:06.870 --> 00:54:08.530
There's only peat bogs.

00:54:08.530 --> 00:54:10.790
So when they do the malting
process and they dry the

00:54:10.790 --> 00:54:13.440
barley, they're using peat
to light those flames.

00:54:13.440 --> 00:54:14.510
That's number one.

00:54:14.510 --> 00:54:19.590
Number two, all of the air here
is full of salt, right?

00:54:19.590 --> 00:54:20.790
Because you're on the coast.

00:54:20.790 --> 00:54:24.240
And that salted air will
permeate the casks, because

00:54:24.240 --> 00:54:28.870
wood is porous, and get into
the casks and impart a

00:54:28.870 --> 00:54:30.620
saltiness to the scotch.

00:54:30.620 --> 00:54:33.740
If you go into the Highlands
now, this is a much more

00:54:33.740 --> 00:54:36.150
forested, wooded area.

00:54:36.150 --> 00:54:39.970
The water is much cleaner and
purer than you're going to get

00:54:39.970 --> 00:54:40.910
on the coast.

00:54:40.910 --> 00:54:44.610
You guys have all had water in
Florida, or Virginia Beach, or

00:54:44.610 --> 00:54:45.560
the Hamptons.

00:54:45.560 --> 00:54:48.550
Totally different character
from water that's

00:54:48.550 --> 00:54:49.860
from upstate New York.

00:54:49.860 --> 00:54:51.900
Exact same thing
going on here.

00:54:51.900 --> 00:54:55.750
Also, the vegetation is very
different in these regions.

00:54:55.750 --> 00:54:59.220
And you've heard the term
terroir with wine.

00:54:59.220 --> 00:55:02.610
It has to do with if you boil
down to the science of what

00:55:02.610 --> 00:55:05.530
terroir is, it's the
local chemicals.

00:55:05.530 --> 00:55:09.840
It's things in the local plants,
things in the local

00:55:09.840 --> 00:55:12.260
soil, mineral formations.

00:55:12.260 --> 00:55:14.850
All those things that vary from
region to region, whether

00:55:14.850 --> 00:55:16.860
it's clay soil, whether
it's rocky soil,

00:55:16.860 --> 00:55:18.070
whether it's sandy soil.

00:55:18.070 --> 00:55:21.870
So all of these things are going
to manifest themselves,

00:55:21.870 --> 00:55:25.560
not only in the water, but in
the actual grain and sometimes

00:55:25.560 --> 00:55:27.190
in the air, and in the wood.

00:55:27.190 --> 00:55:30.150
So all of that will combine
to change the

00:55:30.150 --> 00:55:33.394
character of the scotch.

00:55:33.394 --> 00:55:35.060
AUDIENCE: I think I missed
something about the

00:55:35.060 --> 00:55:35.774
distillation.

00:55:35.774 --> 00:55:38.154
So you said that the output
there is almost

00:55:38.154 --> 00:55:40.550
100% alcohol, right?

00:55:40.550 --> 00:55:41.720
ANTHONY CAPORALE:
Here, not quite.

00:55:41.720 --> 00:55:43.100
But, let's pretend.

00:55:43.100 --> 00:55:46.730
AUDIENCE: But then how do
you get to the 40%?

00:55:46.730 --> 00:55:48.090
ANTHONY CAPORALE:
Good question.

00:55:48.090 --> 00:55:49.810
Really good question,
great question.

00:55:49.810 --> 00:55:50.900
You didn't miss it.

00:55:50.900 --> 00:55:52.540
I skipped it because we're
trying to do this in a short

00:55:52.540 --> 00:55:53.340
amount of time.

00:55:53.340 --> 00:55:56.560
When you pull it out of the
barrel, it will come out of

00:55:56.560 --> 00:56:05.910
the barrel at, let's call it 115
to 120 proof, 60% alcohol.

00:56:05.910 --> 00:56:10.930
You then will take it and add
water to that whisky that you

00:56:10.930 --> 00:56:12.340
pulled out of the barrel
before you

00:56:12.340 --> 00:56:14.100
put it in the bottle.

00:56:14.100 --> 00:56:16.240
You'll actually, what
they call reduce

00:56:16.240 --> 00:56:18.300
it, by adding water.

00:56:18.300 --> 00:56:21.750
That water that you add will
also affect the flavor.

00:56:21.750 --> 00:56:25.790
It used to be that you were
making scotch up here.

00:56:25.790 --> 00:56:27.280
You would pull the scotch
out of the barrel.

00:56:27.280 --> 00:56:30.150
You would add water from this
region into the bottle, and

00:56:30.150 --> 00:56:31.630
then you would ship it.

00:56:31.630 --> 00:56:33.980
What they do now, unfortunately,
is they take

00:56:33.980 --> 00:56:34.840
the scotch from here.

00:56:34.840 --> 00:56:36.730
They put in a tanker truck.

00:56:36.730 --> 00:56:39.530
And then they ship it
down to Glasgow.

00:56:39.530 --> 00:56:41.520
And then they take scotch from
here, they put it in a tanker

00:56:41.520 --> 00:56:43.900
truck, and they ship
it down to Glasgow.

00:56:43.900 --> 00:56:47.660
Once it gets to Glasgow, they
take Glaswegian water, fill up

00:56:47.660 --> 00:56:50.320
the bottles, and then ship it
to the rest of the world.

00:56:50.320 --> 00:56:52.550
Because it's a lot
cheaper that way.

00:56:52.550 --> 00:56:54.430
OK, but really, really
good question.

00:56:54.430 --> 00:56:56.510
So we're always adding
water before we put

00:56:56.510 --> 00:56:57.415
it back in the bottle.

00:56:57.415 --> 00:56:59.350
AUDIENCE: What regulation
is there for that?

00:56:59.350 --> 00:57:01.010
ANTHONY CAPORALE: There is
no regulation for that.

00:57:01.010 --> 00:57:03.665
And I'm not supposed to tell you
that, but I love you guys.

00:57:06.170 --> 00:57:08.280
It's one of the dirty
secrets of scotch.

00:57:08.280 --> 00:57:12.750
AUDIENCE: How do you make sure
there's no methanol in there?

00:57:12.750 --> 00:57:14.550
ANTHONY CAPORALE: Very,
very good question.

00:57:14.550 --> 00:57:16.350
So the methanol is actually
going to be in the

00:57:16.350 --> 00:57:17.730
heads and the tails.

00:57:17.730 --> 00:57:20.780
So the question is how do you
make sure there's no methanol,

00:57:20.780 --> 00:57:22.400
which is wood alcohol.

00:57:22.400 --> 00:57:23.342
And there is.

00:57:23.342 --> 00:57:25.090
It will be in the heads
and the tails.

00:57:25.090 --> 00:57:27.690
So you have to be very
careful what you cut.

00:57:27.690 --> 00:57:29.640
It's one of the things you have
to make sure that you're

00:57:29.640 --> 00:57:31.420
not including methanol
in your cut.

00:57:31.420 --> 00:57:33.820
AUDIENCE: So the producers
have a test probably,

00:57:33.820 --> 00:57:34.780
afterwards?

00:57:34.780 --> 00:57:35.110
ANTHONY CAPORALE: Yeah.

00:57:35.110 --> 00:57:38.220
And they're actually
ridiculous at it.

00:57:38.220 --> 00:57:41.110
These guys, they can
tell by smell.

00:57:41.110 --> 00:57:44.490
These guys have been doing this
for like 40, 50 years.

00:57:44.490 --> 00:57:47.140
What they'll do is at some
point in the distillation

00:57:47.140 --> 00:57:50.800
process, there's an
open container.

00:57:50.800 --> 00:57:53.400
And they'll actually
dip and smell.

00:57:53.400 --> 00:57:54.830
You would think that
they would be doing

00:57:54.830 --> 00:57:57.230
like a chemical test.

00:57:57.230 --> 00:58:00.190
I was hoping they were doing a
chemical-- but they're not.

00:58:00.190 --> 00:58:04.190
They can actually smell, and
they'll know where in the cut

00:58:04.190 --> 00:58:06.270
they are just by smell.

00:58:06.270 --> 00:58:08.965
It's really, it's crazy.

00:58:08.965 --> 00:58:10.390
AUDIENCE: Well now, I
have two questions.

00:58:10.390 --> 00:58:13.240
So why is it in the head and
the tail, instead of one

00:58:13.240 --> 00:58:14.660
according to the boiling?

00:58:14.660 --> 00:58:16.610
ANTHONY CAPORALE:
No, it's not.

00:58:16.610 --> 00:58:19.120
Methanol is going
to be in the--

00:58:19.120 --> 00:58:20.140
I'm going to get this wrong.

00:58:20.140 --> 00:58:24.130
I think methanol is going
to be in the tails.

00:58:24.130 --> 00:58:25.430
It's one or the other.

00:58:25.430 --> 00:58:27.620
I forget which one
it is though.

