What's that?

00:58:28.410 --> 00:58:30.600
AUDIENCE: --region water thing,
so we can taste the

00:58:30.600 --> 00:58:30.770
difference?

00:58:30.770 --> 00:58:31.270
ANTHONY CAPORALE: Is what?

00:58:31.270 --> 00:58:33.174
AUDIENCE: Are there any brands
that don't use the Glaswegian

00:58:33.174 --> 00:58:35.080
water so we can taste
the difference?

00:58:35.080 --> 00:58:36.981
ANTHONY CAPORALE: Edradour
doesn't.

00:58:36.981 --> 00:58:37.843
And--

00:58:37.843 --> 00:58:40.140
AUDIENCE:Talisker insisted
that they use--

00:58:40.140 --> 00:58:40.590
ANTHONY CAPORALE: Right.

00:58:40.590 --> 00:58:41.430
Talisker doesn't.

00:58:41.430 --> 00:58:43.050
There's a few brands
that don't, but the

00:58:43.050 --> 00:58:45.793
majority of them do.

00:58:45.793 --> 00:58:47.482
AUDIENCE: Where are you getting
the ABV, are you using

00:58:47.482 --> 00:58:48.950
a hydrometer, a refractometer?

00:58:48.950 --> 00:58:49.900
ANTHONY CAPORALE: Yes.

00:58:49.900 --> 00:58:52.702
They're using a hydrometer.

00:58:52.702 --> 00:58:55.630
AUDIENCE: So wine usually
ages in the bottles.

00:58:55.630 --> 00:58:59.046
Does whisky have that
aging quality?

00:58:59.046 --> 00:59:01.974
So once the whisky's put in the
bottle, does it over time

00:59:01.974 --> 00:59:04.440
get [INAUDIBLE] character,
or not really?

00:59:04.440 --> 00:59:07.360
ANTHONY CAPORALE: Once you put
in a bottle, it becomes

00:59:07.360 --> 00:59:10.260
completely non-reactive.

00:59:10.260 --> 00:59:10.940
Was that your question?

00:59:10.940 --> 00:59:12.495
AUDIENCE: But wine, for example,
you also put it in

00:59:12.495 --> 00:59:14.718
the bottle, and it doesn't
really react, but what happens

00:59:14.718 --> 00:59:16.694
is there are substances
which break down, and

00:59:16.694 --> 00:59:18.176
that's how it ages.

00:59:18.176 --> 00:59:21.140
So does whisky have anything
like that?

00:59:21.140 --> 00:59:21.760
ANTHONY CAPORALE: No.

00:59:21.760 --> 00:59:24.910
Once you put whisky in a bottle,
everything stops.

00:59:24.910 --> 00:59:26.600
So whisky can last--

00:59:26.600 --> 00:59:30.730
unlike wine, whisky actually
will last almost indefinitely

00:59:30.730 --> 00:59:32.075
if it's sealed properly
in a bottle.

00:59:32.075 --> 00:59:35.450
It's completely non-reactive
once it's in the bottle.

00:59:35.450 --> 00:59:37.610
It has to do with the fact that
there's less solids in

00:59:37.610 --> 00:59:40.290
it, and there's much higher
alcohol content.

00:59:40.290 --> 00:59:43.120
If you're familiar with things
like port and sherry, which

00:59:43.120 --> 00:59:45.650
are what we call fortified wines
where they actually add

00:59:45.650 --> 00:59:49.490
alcohol back to the wine, the
reason they do that is so that

00:59:49.490 --> 00:59:51.860
when you put it in a bottle, it
will last longer, and then

00:59:51.860 --> 00:59:53.070
you can ship it.

00:59:53.070 --> 00:59:57.670
Port and sherry was actually
developed for shipping, some

00:59:57.670 --> 00:59:59.310
of the first products that were
specifically developed

00:59:59.310 --> 01:00:00.550
for export.

01:00:00.550 --> 01:00:01.680
And that's one of
the reasons why.

01:00:01.680 --> 01:00:03.900
You increase the alcohol
content, it lasts longer in

01:00:03.900 --> 01:00:04.841
the bottle.

01:00:04.841 --> 01:00:06.314
AUDIENCE: You may have
said this earlier.

01:00:06.314 --> 01:00:10.242
But I see Drambuie on
the logo, so where

01:00:10.242 --> 01:00:12.210
does that come in?

01:00:12.210 --> 01:00:12.880
ANTHONY CAPORALE:
Great question.

01:00:12.880 --> 01:00:14.200
I probably should have talked
about that more,

01:00:14.200 --> 01:00:17.720
since that's my brand.

01:00:17.720 --> 01:00:20.430
So Drambuie, just so that you
know, I am the national brand

01:00:20.430 --> 01:00:21.630
ambassador for Drambuie.

01:00:21.630 --> 01:00:26.070
Drambuie is a scotch liqueur,
which means it's scotch that

01:00:26.070 --> 01:00:28.760
has sugar or some sweetener--

01:00:28.760 --> 01:00:30.130
in our case, honey--

01:00:30.130 --> 01:00:31.080
and spices.

01:00:31.080 --> 01:00:34.440
So we have liquors or spirits,
which is what we were talking

01:00:34.440 --> 01:00:35.580
about-- whiskies--

01:00:35.580 --> 01:00:39.680
so rum, vodka, gin, whisky.

01:00:39.680 --> 01:00:42.810
All those things are liquors,
or spirits.

01:00:42.810 --> 01:00:45.910
Then we have liqueurs or
cordials, which are

01:00:45.910 --> 01:00:48.450
essentially spirits that
have sweetener and

01:00:48.450 --> 01:00:49.590
flavors added to them.

01:00:49.590 --> 01:00:52.010
And those are things like
Frangelico, Chambord,

01:00:52.010 --> 01:00:55.260
Cointreau, Gran Marnier,
and Drambuie.

01:00:55.260 --> 01:00:57.970
So you have to have flavoring
and sweetener in order to be

01:00:57.970 --> 01:01:01.450
called a liqueur or cordial,
interchangeable.

01:01:01.450 --> 01:01:04.330
Drambuie happens to be a
scotch-based liqueur.

01:01:04.330 --> 01:01:08.470
So it is a blended scotch, 80
proof, blended scotch just

01:01:08.470 --> 01:01:09.430
like Dewar's.

01:01:09.430 --> 01:01:12.270
And we add heather honey
and a proprietary blend

01:01:12.270 --> 01:01:13.600
of herbs and spices.

01:01:13.600 --> 01:01:15.760
And you will taste
that upstairs.

01:01:15.760 --> 01:01:19.580
And you can taste it straight,
and we also have cocktails.

01:01:19.580 --> 01:01:23.120
And we also have a new product
called Drambuie 15, which is a

01:01:23.120 --> 01:01:29.200
15-year-old Speyside single
malt, not a blended scotch.

01:01:29.200 --> 01:01:31.160
It is actually a blend
of single malts.

01:01:31.160 --> 01:01:32.290
And they're all 15 years old.

01:01:32.290 --> 01:01:33.670
And they're all from Speyside.

01:01:33.670 --> 01:01:36.900
And to that, we then add our
Drambuie elixir, which is the

01:01:36.900 --> 01:01:38.110
sweetener and the herbs.

01:01:38.110 --> 01:01:41.260
But it is a scotch, and that's
one of the reasons why I'm

01:01:41.260 --> 01:01:43.742
sort of into this whole
scotch thing.

01:01:43.742 --> 01:01:45.540
AUDIENCE: If I'm a home beer
brewer, I can make a decent

01:01:45.540 --> 01:01:46.772
batch of beer in
a week or two.

01:01:46.772 --> 01:01:49.441
If I am a home distiller, am I
waiting to make three years to

01:01:49.441 --> 01:01:51.030
make something that
tastes drinkable?

01:01:51.030 --> 01:01:51.960
ANTHONY CAPORALE: You're
not allowed to be

01:01:51.960 --> 01:01:53.720
making whisky at home.

01:01:53.720 --> 01:01:54.100
[LAUGHTER]

01:01:54.100 --> 01:01:55.700
ANTHONY CAPORALE: That's
number one.

01:01:55.700 --> 01:01:58.180
Number two, no.

01:01:58.180 --> 01:02:00.770
You can make your beer.

01:02:00.770 --> 01:02:02.540
You can distill it
very quickly.

01:02:02.540 --> 01:02:05.600
If you want to age it in a cask,
you're probably looking

01:02:05.600 --> 01:02:08.390
at about five years.

01:02:08.390 --> 01:02:08.800
I don't know.

01:02:08.800 --> 01:02:09.570
I've never tried it.

01:02:09.570 --> 01:02:10.907
I swear though.

01:02:10.907 --> 01:02:12.815
AUDIENCE: Will you tell us a
little bit about you know,

01:02:12.815 --> 01:02:15.680
some people say drink it
on the rocks, versus--

01:02:15.680 --> 01:02:17.550
ANTHONY CAPORALE: Yes, good.

01:02:17.550 --> 01:02:18.610
Guys, you got do me a favor.

01:02:18.610 --> 01:02:20.480
If you really want to learn more
about this than I can do

01:02:20.480 --> 01:02:22.070
in an hour, take
my class at the

01:02:22.070 --> 01:02:23.170
Institute of Culinary Education.

01:02:23.170 --> 01:02:24.330
We do three hours of this.

01:02:24.330 --> 01:02:25.660
You taste 35 different
whiskies.

01:02:25.660 --> 01:02:27.740
It's really, really great.

01:02:27.740 --> 01:02:30.210
And I will get even
deeper into this.

01:02:30.210 --> 01:02:33.070
But one of the things that I
will tell you, when you taste

01:02:33.070 --> 01:02:37.390
spirits, particularly whiskies,
please open them up.

01:02:37.390 --> 01:02:39.380
So that means add
water to them.

01:02:39.380 --> 01:02:41.670
So if you have ever have-- if
any of you guys have a friend

01:02:41.670 --> 01:02:43.130
when you go out and you
order whisky, and

01:02:43.130 --> 01:02:44.420
then you look at them.

01:02:44.420 --> 01:02:46.540
And you want ice, but you won't
because you're with

01:02:46.540 --> 01:02:48.370
them, and you know they're going
to laugh, don't hang out

01:02:48.370 --> 01:02:49.810
with that person anymore.

01:02:49.810 --> 01:02:52.010
Because they don't have your
best interests at heart.

01:02:52.010 --> 01:02:53.380
I want you to add water.

01:02:53.380 --> 01:02:56.870
When you do tastings with
distillers, with the guys who

01:02:56.870 --> 01:03:00.770
make this stuff, if you sit down
at a distillery with the

01:03:00.770 --> 01:03:03.190
master distiller, he's going to
give you a glass of whisky,

01:03:03.190 --> 01:03:06.560
a glass of water, and
a medicine dropper.

01:03:06.560 --> 01:03:09.370
And he wants you to add
water to the whisky.

01:03:09.370 --> 01:03:09.780
All right?

01:03:09.780 --> 01:03:13.990
80 proof is a number that we
came up with for shipping, not

01:03:13.990 --> 01:03:15.470
for drinking.

01:03:15.470 --> 01:03:15.930
OK?

01:03:15.930 --> 01:03:17.020
It's for shipping.

01:03:17.020 --> 01:03:18.790
We want you to open it up.

01:03:18.790 --> 01:03:20.280
So add water, add ice.

01:03:20.280 --> 01:03:24.790
I tell people up to equal
parts water is fine.

01:03:24.790 --> 01:03:28.330
If you drink 80 proof whisky,
your mouth, it burns.

01:03:28.330 --> 01:03:28.940
It does.

01:03:28.940 --> 01:03:30.340
And it's supposed to.

01:03:30.340 --> 01:03:31.590
Because it's toxic, remember?

01:03:31.590 --> 01:03:32.970
I put that up early on.

01:03:32.970 --> 01:03:33.790
It's toxic.

01:03:33.790 --> 01:03:37.520
So what you'll see is if you
do this with a master

01:03:37.520 --> 01:03:39.870
distiller, you put a drop of
water, and then you taste it.

01:03:39.870 --> 01:03:41.850
Then you put another drop of
water, and you taste it.

01:03:41.850 --> 01:03:43.450
And you keep doing that.

01:03:43.450 --> 01:03:46.610
One drop along the line, all of
a sudden the burn's going

01:03:46.610 --> 01:03:47.250
to go away.

01:03:47.250 --> 01:03:48.890
It's just going to shut off.

01:03:48.890 --> 01:03:50.320
It may be 12 drops for you.

01:03:50.320 --> 01:03:51.880
It may be 20 drops for you.

01:03:51.880 --> 01:03:55.190
But it's going to be the same
every time for each person.

01:03:55.190 --> 01:03:57.510
And that's called your
alcohol threshold.

01:03:57.510 --> 01:03:59.500
So what they ask you to do is
write that number down.

01:03:59.500 --> 01:04:01.130
And then the next time they
give you sample, put those

01:04:01.130 --> 01:04:03.110
number of drops in and
then taste it.

01:04:03.110 --> 01:04:03.420
OK?

01:04:03.420 --> 01:04:06.420
Because if you don't do that,
you're not tasting anything.

01:04:06.420 --> 01:04:10.320
All your tongue is telling you
is, this is poison, spit it

01:04:10.320 --> 01:04:11.670
out, please.

01:04:11.670 --> 01:04:12.990
We don't want that.

01:04:12.990 --> 01:04:14.440
So add water.

01:04:14.440 --> 01:04:15.480
I add ice.

01:04:15.480 --> 01:04:18.230
I only drink whisky
with full rocks.

01:04:18.230 --> 01:04:19.890
That's how I like it.

01:04:19.890 --> 01:04:21.760
And believe me, I know
what I'm doing.

01:04:21.760 --> 01:04:25.360
So please, water and
ice to taste.

01:04:25.360 --> 01:04:28.290
There's nothing wrong with
drinking what we call neat,

01:04:28.290 --> 01:04:30.140
which is right from the
bottle into the glass.

01:04:30.140 --> 01:04:31.010
That's fine.

01:04:31.010 --> 01:04:33.670
But if you don't enjoy that--
and most people don't--

01:04:33.670 --> 01:04:36.390
please, please, please
add water, add ice,

01:04:36.390 --> 01:04:37.510
until you enjoy it.

01:04:37.510 --> 01:04:38.830
That's what we want you to do.

01:04:38.830 --> 01:04:40.530
Thanks for asking that.

01:04:40.530 --> 01:04:41.695
Anything else?

01:04:41.695 --> 01:04:43.810
You guys thirsty?

01:04:43.810 --> 01:04:45.230
Let's go.

01:04:45.230 --> 01:04:51.803
[APPLAUSE]

